@Node "Requirements" "TSMorph.guide/Requirements"
@Next "Par"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Software and Hardware required
******************************

The following libraries (with minimum version) are required to run
TSMorph:

     intuition.library        37
     iffparse.library         37
     graphics.library         37
     layers.library           37
     gadtools.library         37
     asl.library              37
     utility.library          37
     diskfont.library         36
     icon.library             37
     rexxsyslib.library       0

The following will also be used if present:

     amigaguide.library       34
     opal.library             0  Note: OpalVision board is not required
     reqtools.library         38 reqtools is ©1991/1992 Nico François
                                 This is required for Animated Warps/Morphs

TSMorph-render requires a large amount of chip memory (or
opal.library). If you have 1Mb then 512x512 images can be morphed
(though you may have to run workbench on a 2 colour 640x200 screen).
640x512 is probably impossible without 2Mb of chip memory.

The amount of chip memory required by TSMorph can be reduced to 1/5 by
setting the @{"ZOOM" Link "P-ZOOM"} parameter to OFF.


@EndNode

@Node "Par" "TSMorph.guide/Par"
@Next "Info"
@Prev "Requirements"
@Toc "Main"

Tool types and Shell parameters
*******************************

Both TSMorph and TSMorph-render can be run from the Shell or the
Workbench. Most be edited using the @{"Settings" Link "men-Settings"} menu.

NOTE: TSMorph and TSMorph-render both require a stack size of more than
4096. 8192 should be OK. If the stack is set large enought then the
programs will probable just crash.

Parameters can be supplied, normally either on the Shell command line,
as Icon Tool Types on the Project, TSMorph or TSMorph-render Icon, or
in a settings file.

The format of settings files is a text file with lines in the format:

     Settingstype=settingsvalue

Blank lines or lines starting with a ; (semi-colon) are treated as
comments. Any settings supplied on the Shell command line or as an Icon
Tool Type override values specified in this file. Parameters on the
Project Icon override parameters on the Tool Icon.

Note: All the Project Icon tool types are used if the project is run
with a default tool or by double clicking a tool, some are are not used
if the project is selected using a file requester, if the Tool was run
from the Shell then file requester selected project tool types are
ignored. Also some settings can not be changed on open projects,

The Settings file name used is first file found from:

     1) The name supplied in the SETTINGS= parameter on the project.
     1) The name supplied in the SETTINGS= parameter on the tool.
     2) TSMorph.prefs
        in the project directory for the workbench,
        the current directory from the Shell.
     3) TSMorph.prefs
        in the directory TSMorph was loaded from.
     4) ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs

Unless @{"KEEPSETTINGS" Link "P-KEEPSETTINGS"} is set to NO current settings are saved in
ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs when TSMorph is quit. Settings cann be saved
and loaded from the @{"Settings" Link "men-Settings"} menu.


 @{" TSMorph " Link "Par-TSMorph"}                          Parameters to TSMorph
 @{" TSMorph-render " Link "Par-TSMorph-render"}                   Parameters to TSMorph-render


@EndNode

@Node "Par-TSMorph" "TSMorph.guide/Par-TSMorph"
@Next "Par-TSMorph-render"
@Toc "Par"

Parameters to TSMorph
=====================

The following parameters can be supplied, normally either on the Shell
command line, as Icon Tool Types on the Project or TSMorph Icon, or in
a settings file:


 @{" CHANGEPALETTE " Link "P-CHANGEPALETTE"}                Change screen palette to match image
 @{" CREATEICONS " Link "P-CREATEICONS"}                  Create project Icons
 @{" CREATEICONSP " Link "P-CREATEICONSP"}                 Create prefs Icons
 @{" FILES " Link "P-FILES"}                        Specify file to open
 @{" KEEPSETTINGS " Link "P-KEEPSETTINGS"}                 Save settings on Quit
 @{" OPENMODE " Link "P-OPENMODE"}                     How to open images
 @{" PUBSCREEN " Link "P-PUBSCREEN"}                    Public screen to use
 @{" SETTINGS " Link "P-SETTINGS"}                     Settings file name
 @{" ZOOM " Link "P-ZOOM"}                         Zoom image 2 times


@EndNode

@Node "P-CHANGEPALETTE" "TSMorph.guide/P-CHANGEPALETTE"
@Next "P-CREATEICONS"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

CHANGEPALETTE=YES/NO/OFF
------------------------

Sets the default value of the Change Palette? settings menu item -
defaults to YES.

This item toggles if each images palette should be used to display the
image when the window is active. Each image window can have its own
palette.

Since the ability to change screens colour palettes is not supported by
CBM this menu option can be disabled by setting this parameter to OFF.


@EndNode

@Node "P-CREATEICONS" "TSMorph.guide/P-CREATEICONS"
@Next "P-CREATEICONSP"
@Prev "P-CHANGEPALETTE"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

CREATEICONS=YES/NO
------------------

Sets the default value of the Create Icons? settings menu item -
defaults to YES.

This item toggles if Icons are to be saved with @{"parameter files" Link "File_Format"}. If it
is selected then an Icon will be saved. The icon will come from
'ENV:TSMorph/def_points' if this exists, secondly from
'ENV:SYS/def_points', otherwise the default project Icon is used.

This parameter is not changed by Requester loaded projects.


@EndNode

@Node "P-CREATEICONSP" "TSMorph.guide/P-CREATEICONSP"
@Next "P-FILES"
@Prev "P-CREATEICONS"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

CREATEICONSP=YES/NO
-------------------

Sets the default value of the Create Prefs Icons? settings menu item -
defaults to YES.

This item toggles if Icons are to be saved with @{"Settings" Link "Par"} files. If it is
selected then an Icon will be saved. The icon will come from
'ENV:TSMorph/def_prefs' if this exists, secondly from
'ENV:SYS/def_prefs', otherwise the default project Icon is used.


@EndNode

@Node "P-FILES" "TSMorph.guide/P-FILES"
@Next "P-KEEPSETTINGS"
@Prev "P-CREATEICONSP"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

FILES=filename
--------------

This is only relevant to the Shell, only one name can be supplied -
default is to open a new unnamed project.

Only one filename can be supplied.


@EndNode

@Node "P-KEEPSETTINGS" "TSMorph.guide/P-KEEPSETTINGS"
@Next "P-OPENMODE"
@Prev "P-FILES"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

KEEPSETTINGS=YES/NO
-------------------

By default current settings are saved in 'ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs'
when TSMorph is quit. This parameter and menu item enable this
behaviour to be turned off.

Default value is YES.


@EndNode

@Node "P-OPENMODE" "TSMorph.guide/P-OPENMODE"
@Next "P-PUBSCREEN"
@Prev "P-KEEPSETTINGS"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

OPENMODE=ALWAYS/IFILBM/IFCOLOURS/OPAL
-------------------------------------

This parameter and menu item specify how images should be loaded for
displaying by TSMorph. It is only relevant if opal.library is present.
If opal.library is not present then only standard ILBM images can be
loaded. Otherwise TSMorph can load any image which opal.library supprts
(EHB,HAM,JPEG,24 bit ILBM). The images are loaded and mapped to the
screens current colour palette.

     ALWAYS    - Only try and load normal ILBM images. Fail if not.
     IFILBM    - First try to load as an ILBM image, try opal.library
                 if the image is not an ILBM or has 24 planes.
     IFCOLOURS - As IFILBM but use opal.library if the number of planes
                 in the image exceed the number of the screen.
     OPAL      - Always use opal.library to load the image.

Using opal.library to load the image means most images can be loaded.
However the load process may be slow as the images are loaded and
converted to 24 bit internally and the remapped to the screen palette.

An alternative is to use the @{"Loadscript" Link "AR-Loadscript"} ARexx script to convert each
image before loading.


@EndNode

@Node "P-PUBSCREEN" "TSMorph.guide/P-PUBSCREEN"
@Next "P-SETTINGS"
@Prev "P-OPENMODE"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

PUBSCREEN=pubscreenname
-----------------------

This gives the name of the Public Screen on which to open all TSMorph
windows - default is the default public screen.

This parameter is not changed by Requester loaded projects.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the screen
name, but any change is ignored until TSMorph is reloaded.


@EndNode

@Node "P-SETTINGS" "TSMorph.guide/P-SETTINGS"
@Next "P-ZOOM"
@Prev "P-PUBSCREEN"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

SETTINGS=filename
-----------------

This can only be supplied on the Shell command line, or an Icon Tool
Type. It specifies the name of a file for more parameters. See
@{"parameters" Link "Par"}.

This parameter is not changed by Requester loaded projects.


@EndNode

@Node "P-ZOOM" "TSMorph.guide/P-ZOOM"
@Prev "P-SETTINGS"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph"

ZOOM=YES/NO/OFF
---------------

Sets the default value of the Zoom? settings menu item. If set to YES
then images will be initially displayed 2x normal size, if set to NO
then images will be initially displayed normal size, setting to OFF
disables the Zoom? option, this reduces chip memory usage to 1/5 -
defaults to NO.


@EndNode

@Node "Par-TSMorph-render" "TSMorph.guide/Par-TSMorph-render"
@Prev "Par-TSMorph"
@Toc "Par"

Parameters to TSMorph-render
============================

The following parameters can be supplied, normally either on the Shell
command line, as Icon Tool Types on the Project or TSMorph-render Icon,
or in a settings file:


 @{" CREATEICONSR " Link "P-CREATEICONSR"}               Create image Icons
 @{" DEPTH " Link "P-DEPTH"}                      Depth for search algorithm
 @{" DX " Link "P-DX"}                         Horizontal Pixelation
 @{" DY " Link "P-DY"}                         Vertical Pixelation
 @{" FILES " Link "P-FILES-R"}                      Specify file to open
 @{" LOADSCRIPT " Link "P-LOADSCRIPT"}                 Script before each image loaded
 @{" MODE " Link "P-MODE"}                       Mode for rendering algorithm
 @{" POSTSCRIPT " Link "P-POSTSCRIPT"}                 Script after rendering frame
 @{" PRESCRIPT " Link "P-PRESCRIPT"}                  Script before rendering frame
 @{" PUBSCREENR " Link "P-PUBSCREENR"}                 Public screen to use
 @{" QUALITY " Link "P-QUALITY"}                    JPEG Quality
 @{" SAVEFORMAT " Link "P-SAVEFORMAT"}                 Format to save images
 @{" SETTINGS " Link "P-SETTINGS-R"}                   Settings file name
 @{" TOOLPRI " Link "P-TOOLPRI"}                    Priority of TSMorph-render


@EndNode

@Node "P-CREATEICONSR" "TSMorph.guide/P-CREATEICONSR"
@Next "P-DEPTH"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

CREATEICONSR=NO/YES
-------------------

This parameter and menu item selects if Icons are to be saved with
image files. If it is YES then an Icon will be saved. The icon depends
on the @{"save format" Link "P-SAVEFORMAT"}.

     'ENV:TSMorph/def_ilbm' - 24 bit ILBM saved without opal.library
     'ENV:TSMorph/def_iff'  - 24 bit ILBM saved using opal.library
     'ENV:TSMorph/def_jpg'  - JPEG files saved using opal.library
     'ENV:TSMorph/def_ppm'  - PPM files

If the file does not exist then 'ENV:SYS/def_ilbm' (etc.) is tried, if
this does not exist then the default project Icon is used.

Default value is NO.


@EndNode

@Node "P-DEPTH" "TSMorph.guide/P-DEPTH"
@Next "P-DX"
@Prev "P-CREATEICONSR"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

DEPTH=number
------------

This parameter indicates how deep the Morphing @{"algorithm" Link "Algorithms"} should search
to find the points to use for morphing.

Default value is 2.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-DX" "TSMorph.guide/P-DX"
@Next "P-DY"
@Prev "P-DEPTH"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

DX=number
---------

This parameter can be used to speed up the rendering process. The
default value is 0.

If set to a number then only some Horizontal pixels will be generated.
e.g. if set to 3 then only every 4th pixel will be generated. The
others will be copied from the previous pixel. This can be overridden
by using @{"ARexx" Link "AR-Prescript"}. Also see @{"DY" Link "P-DY"}.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-DY" "TSMorph.guide/P-DY"
@Next "P-FILES-R"
@Prev "P-DX"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

DY=number
---------

This parameter can be used to speed up the rendering process. The
default value is 0.

If set to a number then only some Vertical pixels will be generated.
e.g. if set to 1 then only every other line will be generated. The
others will be copied from the previous line. This can be overridden by
using @{"ARexx" Link "AR-Prescript"}. Also see @{"DX" Link "P-DX"}.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-FILES-R" "TSMorph.guide/P-FILES-R"
@Next "P-LOADSCRIPT"
@Prev "P-DY"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

FILES=filename
--------------

This is only relevant to the Shell, only one name can be supplied -
default is to show an ASL file requester for the file to run.

Only one filename can be supplied.


@EndNode

@Node "P-LOADSCRIPT" "TSMorph.guide/P-LOADSCRIPT"
@Next "P-MODE"
@Prev "P-FILES-R"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

LOADSCRIPT=Scriptname/OFF
-------------------------

This specifies the name of an @{"ARexx" Link "AR-Loadscript"} script to run before each image 24
bit image is loaded. This can be used to e.g. hold the images on disc
in JPEG format to save space and convert each image back to 24 bit ILBM
when required.

The default script is @{"Rexx/Loadscript" ALINK
"Rexx/Loadscript.TSM/Main}.

The version supplied does nothing.

Set to OFF to run no script.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-MODE" "TSMorph.guide/P-MODE"
@Next "P-POSTSCRIPT"
@Prev "P-LOADSCRIPT"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

MODE=0/1/2/3
------------

This parameter and menu item indicate how the Morphing @{"algorithm" Link "Algorithms"} should
search to find the points to use for morphing.

Default value is 0.


@EndNode

@Node "P-POSTSCRIPT" "TSMorph.guide/P-POSTSCRIPT"
@Next "P-PRESCRIPT"
@Prev "P-MODE"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

POSTSCRIPT=Scriptname/OFF
-------------------------

This specifies the name of an @{"ARexx" Link "AR-Prescript"} script to run after each image is
rendered. This can be used to build an animation or change the image
format from 24 bit.

The default script is @{"Rexx/Postscript" ALINK
"Rexx/Postscript.TSM/Main}.

The version supplied does nothing.

Set to OFF to run no script.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-PRESCRIPT" "TSMorph.guide/P-PRESCRIPT"
@Next "P-PUBSCREENR"
@Prev "P-POSTSCRIPT"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

PRESCRIPT=Scriptname/OFF
------------------------

This specifies the name of an @{"ARexx" Link "AR-Prescript"} script to run before each image is
rendered. This can be used to produce only some of the frames and
control the movement and colour of the images.

The default script is @{"Rexx/Prescript" ALINK
"Rexx/Prescript.TSM/Main}.

The version supplied does nothing.

Set to OFF to run no script.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-PUBSCREENR" "TSMorph.guide/P-PUBSCREENR"
@Next "P-QUALITY"
@Prev "P-PRESCRIPT"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

PUBSCREENR=pubscreenname
------------------------

This gives the name of the Public Screen on which to open
TSMorph-render windows - default is the default public screen.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the screen
name.


@EndNode

@Node "P-QUALITY" "TSMorph.guide/P-QUALITY"
@Next "P-SAVEFORMAT"
@Prev "P-PUBSCREENR"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

QUALITY=number
--------------

This specifies the quality of output files. This option only applies if
opal.library is available and @{"SAVEFORMAT" Link "P-SAVEFORMAT"} is JPEG or JPEGT. Possible
values are 0 to 100.

Default value is 75.

It can be changed using the menu item (if reqtools.library is
available), a requester is displayed allowing the input of the value.


@EndNode

@Node "P-SAVEFORMAT" "TSMorph.guide/P-SAVEFORMAT"
@Next "P-SETTINGS-R"
@Prev "P-QUALITY"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

SAVEFORMAT=ILBM24/OPAL24/OPAL24T/OPAL24F/OPAL24FT/JPEG/JPEGT/PPM
----------------------------------------------------------------

This parameter and menu item specify the the format TSMorph-render
should use to save the output images. OPAL and JPEG formats are only
available if opal.library is available.

     ILBM24   - IFF 24 bit ILBM with no CAMG chunk
     OPAL24   - IFF 24 bit ILBM saved using opal.library
     OPAL24T  - as OPAL24 with a Thumbnail
     OPAL24F  - as OPAL24 in Fast Format
     OPAL24TF - as OPAL24F with a Thumbnail
     JPEG     - JPEG format using opal.library
     JPEGT    - as JPEG with a Thumbnail
     PPM      - PPM format

The quality of JPEG images can be set using the @{"QUALITY" Link "P-QUALITY"} parameter.

PPM format is basically uncompressed 24 bit. The files are therefore
very large and it is suggested that a compressing file handler (such as
XFH or EPU) is used. This format is provided mainly to allow the easy
production of MPEG movies.


@EndNode

@Node "P-SETTINGS-R" "TSMorph.guide/P-SETTINGS-R"
@Next "P-TOOLPRI"
@Prev "P-SAVEFORMAT"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

SETTINGS=filename
-----------------

This can only be supplied on the Shell command line, or an Icon Tool
Type.

This specifies the name of a file to contain settings. See @{"parameters" Link "Par"}.


@EndNode

@Node "P-TOOLPRI" "TSMorph.guide/P-TOOLPRI"
@Prev "P-SETTINGS-R"
@Toc "Par-TSMorph-render"

TOOLPRI=number
--------------

This can only be supplied as a Tool Icon tool type. It sets the
priority of the rendering process.

Setting to -1 is a good idea if you wish to run the program in the
background. The default value is 0. Setting to positive values is
generally *not* a good idea.


@EndNode

@Node "Info" "TSMorph.guide/Info"
@Next "Con"
@Prev "Par"
@Toc "Main"

The Information Window
**********************

This window is always displayed when TSMorph is running. It displays
information about the current project. The window title is "TSMorph",
the screen title will be displayed as the project name if the project
has a name. It is used to set up all the information required by
TSMorph-render.


 @{" Gadgets " Link "I-gad"}       Gadgets displayed in the Info Window
 @{" Menus " Link "I-men"}         Menus available in the Info Window
 @{" Keyboard " Link "I-key"}      Keyboard controls in the Info Window


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad"
@Next "I-men"
@Toc "Info"

Gadgets in Info Window
======================

The Information Window appears with gadgets:

     -----------------------------
     |.|TSMorph            |  |  |
     ----------------------------|
     | File One .............  X |
     | File Two .............  X |
     |24 File 1 .............  X |
     |24 File 2 .............  X |
     |    Width ...   Height ... |
     | Single  Frames .. Start . |
     |     Name ............   X |
     |        Edit Points        |
     -----------------------------


 @{" File One " Link "I-gad-File_One"}                        The first image file for point editing
 @{" Get file " Link "I-gad-Get_File_One"}                        Get file gadget for above
 @{" File Two " Link "I-gad-File_Two"}                        The second image file for point editing
 @{" Get File " Link "I-gad-Get_File_Two"}                        Get file gadget for above
 @{" 24 File 1 " Link "I-gad-24_File_1"}                       The first 24 bit image file to morph
 @{" Get File " Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_1"}                        Get file gadget for above
 @{" 24 File 2 " Link "I-gad-24_File_2"}                       The second 24 bit image file to morph
 @{" Get File " Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_2"}                        Get file gadget for above
 @{" Width " Link "I-gad-Width"}                           Read only gadget showing width
 @{" Height " Link "I-gad-Height"}                          Read only gadget showing Height
 @{" Single " Link "I-gad-Single"}                          Checkbox to morph only one image
 @{" Frames " Link "I-gad-Frames"}                          Number of frames to generate
 @{" Start " Link "I-gad-Start"}                           Frame number to start at
 @{" Name " Link "I-gad-Name"}                            File name of animation frames
 @{" Get File " Link "I-gad-Get_Name"}                        Get file gadget for above
 @{" Edit Points... " Link "I-gad-Edit_Points"}                  Display images to edit points

 @{" Close gadget " Link "I-gad-Close"}                    Quit program
 @{" Zoom gadget " Link "I-gad-Zoom"}                     Standard zoom window
 @{" Depth gadget " Link "I-gad-Depth"}                    Standard depth gadget


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-File_One" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-File_One"
@Next "I-gad-Get_File_One"
@Toc "I-gad"

File One gadget
---------------

This gadget allows the editing of the file name of the first image to
be used when editing points. This gadget is disabled if the
@{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"} are currently open. The file name can be either edited in
the string gadget or by using the @{"Get File" Link "I-gad-Get_File_One"} to display an ASL file
requester.

This image should be a Workbench displayable version of the
@{"first 24 bit file" Link "I-gad-24_File_1"}. It is displayed in the first @{"Edit Window" Link "Edit"} when
editing points.

'o' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

See @{"File naming" Link "File_Names"} for how to specify the file name.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Get_File_One" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Get_File_One"
@Next "I-gad-File_Two"
@Prev "I-gad-File_One"
@Toc "I-gad"

Get File One gadget
-------------------

This gadget displays an ASL file requester to select the file to appear
in the @{"File One" Link "I-gad-File_One"} gadget.

'o' with shift is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-File_Two" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-File_Two"
@Next "I-gad-Get_File_Two"
@Prev "I-gad-Get_File_One"
@Toc "I-gad"

File Two gadget
---------------

This gadget is the same as the @{"File One" Link "I-gad-File_One"} gadget for the second
displayable image. This image should be the same size as the first.

't' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

See @{"File naming" Link "File_Names"} for how to specify the file name.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Get_File_Two" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Get_File_Two"
@Next "I-gad-24_File_1"
@Prev "I-gad-File_Two"
@Toc "I-gad"

Get File Two gadget
-------------------

This gadget displays an ASL file requester to select the file to appear
in the @{"File Two" Link "I-gad-File_Two"} gadget.

't' with shift is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-24_File_1" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-24_File_1"
@Next "I-gad-Get_24_File_1"
@Prev "I-gad-Get_File_Two"
@Toc "I-gad"

24 File 1 gadget
----------------

This gadget allows the editing of the file name of the first image to
be used when morphing. The file name can be either edited in the string
gadget or by using the @{"Get File" Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_1"} to display an ASL file requester.

This image should be a 24 bit version of the @{"first displayable file" Link "I-gad-File_One"}.

'1' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

See @{"File naming" Link "File_Names"} for how to specify the file name.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Get_24_File_1" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Get_24_File_1"
@Next "I-gad-24_File_2"
@Prev "I-gad-24_File_1"
@Toc "I-gad"

Get 24 File 1 gadget
--------------------

This gadget displays an ASL file requester to select the file to appear
in the @{"24 File 1" Link "I-gad-24_File_1"} gadget.

'1' with shift is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-24_File_2" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-24_File_2"
@Next "I-gad-Get_24_File_2"
@Prev "I-gad-Get_24_File_1"
@Toc "I-gad"

24 File 2 gadget
----------------

This gadget allows the editing of the file name of the last image to be
used when morphing. The file name can be either edited in the string
gadget or by using the @{"Get File" Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_2"} to display an ASL file requester.

This image should be a 24 bit version of the @{"second displayable file" Link "I-gad-File_Two"}.

If @{"Single Image" Link "I-gad-Single"} mode is selected then this is ignored.

'2' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

See @{"File naming" Link "File_Names"} for how to specify the file name.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Get_24_File_2" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Get_24_File_2"
@Next "I-gad-Width"
@Prev "I-gad-24_File_2"
@Toc "I-gad"

Get 24 File 2 gadget
--------------------

This gadget displays an ASL file requester to select the file to appear
in the @{"24 File 2" Link "I-gad-24_File_2"} gadget.

'2' with shift is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Width" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Width"
@Next "I-gad-Height"
@Prev "I-gad-Get_24_File_2"
@Toc "I-gad"

Width gadget
------------

This gadget displays the width of the images being edited. If images
have not been selected then it should display the maximum width of the
current points.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Height" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Height"
@Next "I-gad-Single"
@Prev "I-gad-Width"
@Toc "I-gad"

Height gadget
-------------

This gadget displays the height of the images being edited. If images
have not been selected then it should display the maximum height of the
current points.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Single" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Single"
@Next "I-gad-Frames"
@Prev "I-gad-Height"
@Toc "I-gad"

Single image gadget
-------------------

This gadget cycles between Morphs, Warps, Animated Morphs and Animated
Warps.

In Warp mode one image is distorted based on the control points.

In Morph mode one image is distorted/recoloured into a second image
based on control points.

In animated Warps and Morphs the input images can change on each output
frame.

'r' and 'R' can be used to cycle this gadget forward and backward - See
@{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

Note: Animated Warps/Morphs are only available if Reqtools is available.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Frames" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Frames"
@Next "I-gad-Start"
@Prev "I-gad-Single"
@Toc "I-gad"

Number of Frames gadget
-----------------------

This gadget can be used to specify the number of frames to generate.

In @{"Single" Link "I-gad-Single"} mode the total number of frames will be this number plus the
first image.

In dual mode the total number of frames is the first image, this number
and the last image.

'f' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

This gadget is disabled if Images are displayed and an animated
Morph/Warp is being editited.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Start" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Start"
@Next "I-gad-Name"
@Prev "I-gad-Frames"
@Toc "I-gad"

Start Frame gadget
------------------

This gadget can be used to specify the number to use in the @{"Name" Link "I-gad-Name"} of the
first generated file. This number is then incremented by 1 for each
subsequent frame.

'a' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

This gadget is disabled if Images are displayed and an animated
Morph/Warp is being editited.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Name" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Name"
@Next "I-gad-Get_Name"
@Prev "I-gad-Start"
@Toc "I-gad"

Anim file Name gadget
---------------------

This gadget is used to name the files produced by TSMorph-render.

The file name can be either edited in the string gadget or by using the
@{"Get File" Link "I-gad-Get_Name"} to display an ASL file requester.

The file name should contain the characters '%ld'. These characters
will be replaced by the frame number, starting from that specified in
the @{"Start" Link "I-gad-Start"} gadget.

'n' can be used to activate this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.

See @{"File naming" Link "File_Names"} for further information on how to specify the file name.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Get_Name" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Get_Name"
@Next "I-gad-Edit_Points"
@Prev "I-gad-Name"
@Toc "I-gad"

Get Anim file Name gadget
-------------------------

This gadget displays an ASL file requester to select the file to appear
in the @{"Name" Link "I-gad-Name"} gadget.

'n' with shift is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Edit_Points" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Edit_Points"
@Next "I-gad-Close"
@Prev "I-gad-Get_Name"
@Toc "I-gad"

Edit Points... gadget
---------------------

This button gadget has the same effect as the @{"Edit Points" Link "I-men-P-Edit_Points"} menu option.
It opens the @{"Control Window" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"} to allow editing of the
control points. If these windows are already open then the Control
Window is activated.

'p' is the same as using this gadget - See @{"Keyboard" Link "I-Key"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Close" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Close"
@Next "I-gad-Zoom"
@Prev "I-gad-Edit_Points"
@Toc "I-gad"

Close gadget
------------

This is a standard close gadget. Clicking quits the program.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Zoom" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Zoom"
@Next "I-gad-Depth"
@Prev "I-gad-Close"
@Toc "I-gad"

Zoom gadget
-----------

This is a standard Zoom gadget which switches the window between full
size and a title bar.


@EndNode

@Node "I-gad-Depth" "TSMorph.guide/I-gad-Depth"
@Prev "I-gad-Zoom"
@Toc "I-gad"

Depth gadget
------------

This is a standard depth gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men" "TSMorph.guide/I-men"
@Next "I-key"
@Prev "I-gad"
@Toc "Info"

Menus on the Info Window
========================

The following menus are available on the Information Window:


 @{" Project " Link "I-men-P"}              Project menu

 @{" Settings " Link "men-Settings"}             Settings menu


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P"
@Toc "I-men"

Info Window Project menu
------------------------

This menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the Info Window:


 @{" New         N " Link "I-men-P-New"}                    Create a new project
 @{" Open...     O " Link "I-men-P-Open"}                    Open a file
 @{" Save        S " Link "I-men-P-Save"}                    Save file
 @{" Save As... " Link "I-men-P-Save_As"}                       Save named file
 @{" Delete... " Link "I-men-P-Delete"}                        Delete a Project
 @{" About... " Link "I-men-P-About"}                         Show about requester
 @{" Quit        Q " Link "I-men-P-Quit"}                    Quit program
 @{" Edit Points E " Link "I-men-P-Edit_Points"}                    Open windows to edit points


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-New" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-New"
@Next "I-men-P-Open"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/New menu item
.................................

This menu item creates a new project.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Open" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Open"
@Next "I-men-P-Save"
@Prev "I-men-P-New"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Open menu item
..................................

This menu item allows the loading of a previously created
@{"Parameter file" Link "File_Format"}.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Save" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Save"
@Next "I-men-P-Save_As"
@Prev "I-men-P-Open"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Save menu item
..................................

This saves the current project using the current name. If the project
does not yet have a name then an ASL file requester is displayed.

See @{"File Format" Link "File_Format"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Save_As" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Save_As"
@Next "I-men-P-Delete"
@Prev "I-men-P-Save"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Save As... menu item
........................................

This saves the current project using a name chosen suing an ASL file
requester.

See @{"File Format" Link "File_Format"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Delete" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Delete"
@Next "I-men-P-About"
@Prev "I-men-P-Save_As"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Delete... menu item
.......................................

This can be used to delete a Project. It will delete the main file, its
icon (if present) and any associated Anim points files.

See @{"File Format" Link "File_Format"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-About" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-About"
@Next "I-men-P-Quit"
@Prev "I-men-P-Delete"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/About... menu item
......................................

This displays some program version information in the @{"About Requester" Link "Req-About"}.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Quit" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Quit"
@Next "I-men-P-Edit_Points"
@Prev "I-men-P-About"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Quit menu item
..................................

This quits TSMorph.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "I-men-P-Edit_Points" "TSMorph.guide/I-men-P-Edit_Points"
@Prev "I-men-P-Quit"
@Toc "I-men-P"

Info Window Project/Edit Points menu item
.........................................

This is the same as the @{"Edit Points" Link "I-gad-Edit_Points"} gadget.

It opens the @{"Control Window" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"} to allow editing of the
control points. If these windows are already open then the Control
Window is activated.


@EndNode

@Node "I-Key" "TSMorph.guide/I-Key"
@Prev "I-men"
@Toc "Info"

Keyboard controls in the Info Window
====================================

The following keyboard controls are available in the Info Window:

     o  Activate @{"File One" Link "I-gad-File_One"} gadget
        With shift - show file requester - See @{"Get File One" Link "I-gad-Get_File_One"}.
     
     t  Activate @{"File Two" Link "I-gad-File_Two"} gadget
        With shift - show file requester - See @{"Get File Two" Link "I-gad-Get_File_Two"}.
     
     1  Activate @{"24 File 1" Link "I-gad-24_File_1"} gadget
        With shift - show file requester - See @{"Get 24 File 1" Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_1"}.
     
     2  Activate @{"24 File 2" Link "I-gad-24_File_2"} gadget
        With shift - show file requester - See @{"Get 24 File 2" Link "I-gad-Get_24_File_2"}.
     
     rR Cycle @{"Single image" Link "I-gad-Single"} gadget.
     
     f  Activate @{"Frames" Link "I-gad-Frames"} gadget.
     
     a  Activate @{"Start" Link "I-gad-Start"} gadget.
     
     n  Activate @{"Name" Link "I-gad-Name"} gadget
        With shift - show file requester - See @{"Get Name" Link "I-gad-Get_Name"}.
     
     p  Same as @{"Edit Points" Link "I-gad-Edit_Points"} gadget

'Help' displays context sensitive help using amigaguide if available.


@EndNode

@Node "Con" "TSMorph.guide/Con"
@Next "Edit"
@Prev "Info"
@Toc "Main"

The Control Window
******************

The control window displays various gadgets for different for different
point editing modes. The title bar displays the current editing mode as
does the Mouse pointer. The screen title bar displays "TSMorph" for
non-animated Warps/Morphs and "TSMorph - Frame nnn" for animated
Warps/Morphs.


 @{" Gadgets " Link "Con-gad"}         Gadgets displayed in the control window
 @{" Menus " Link "CI-men"}           Menus on the Control Window
 @{" Modes " Link "EModes"}           Point editing modes
 @{" Keyboard " Link "Con-key"}        Keyboard controls in the Control Window


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad"
@Toc "Con"

Control and Image Window gadgets
================================

The Control Window appears with gadgets:

     ---------
     |.|Mov| |
     --------|
     |ONE TWO|
     |REL ADD|
     |DEL LNK|
     |UNL MOV|
     ||<<?>>||
     ---------

Most are used to set the edit mode. The rest except the close and depth
gadgets are used to set the current @{"Frame Number" Link "Req-FrameNumber"}.


 @{" One " Link "EMode-One"}                Move points in one window
 @{" Two " Link "EMode-Two"}                Move points in both windows
 @{" Rel " Link "EMode-Relative"}                Move points relatively in both windows
 @{" Add " Link "EMode-Add"}                Add a new point
 @{" Del " Link "EMode-Delete"}                Delete an existing point
 @{" Lnk " Link "EMode-Link"}                Link two points
 @{" Unl " Link "EMode-Unlink"}                Unlink two points
 @{" Mov " Link "EMode-Move"}                Scroll the window

 @{" |< " Link "Con-gad-First"}                 First Frame
 @{" < " Link "Con-gad-Previous"}                  Previous Frame
 @{" ? " Link "Con-gad-Goto"}                  Goto Frame
 @{" > " Link "Con-gad-Next"}                  Next Frame
 @{" >| " Link "Con-gad-Last"}                 Last Frame

 @{" Close " Link "Con-gad-Close"}              Close window
 @{" Depth " Link "Con-gad-Depth"}              Depth gadget


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-First" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-First"
@Next "Con-gad-Previous"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window First Frame gadget
---------------------------------

This gadget goes to the first frame. This is the same as the @{"First" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-First"} menu
item.

This gadget is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the first
frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Previous" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Previous"
@Next "Con-gad-Goto"
@Prev "Con-gad-First"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Previous Frame gadget
------------------------------------

This gadget goes to the previous frame. This is the same as the
@{"Previous" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Previous"} menu item.

This gadget is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the first
frame is currently displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Goto" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Goto"
@Next "Con-gad-Next"
@Prev "Con-gad-Previous"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Goto Frame gadget
--------------------------------

This gadget goes to a chosen frame. This is the same as the @{"Goto" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Goto"} menu
item. It displays the @{"Frame Number" Link "Req-FrameNumber"} Requester.

This gadget is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Next" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Next"
@Next "Con-gad-Last"
@Prev "Con-gad-Goto"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Next Frame gadget
--------------------------------

This gadget goes to the next frame. This is the same as the @{"Next" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Next"} menu
item.

This gadget is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the last
frame is currently displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Last" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Last"
@Next "Con-gad-Close"
@Prev "Con-gad-Next"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Last Frame gadget
--------------------------------

This gadget goes to the last frame. This is the same as the @{"Last" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Last"} menu
item.

This gadget is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the last
frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Close" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Close"
@Next "Con-gad-Depth"
@Prev "Con-gad-Last"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Close gadget
---------------------------

This closes the @{"Control Window" Link "Con"}, and the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-gad-Depth" "TSMorph.guide/Con-gad-Depth"
@Prev "Con-gad-Close"
@Toc "Con-gad"

Control Window Depth gadget
---------------------------

This is a standard depth gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men"
@Toc "Con"

Control and Edit Windows menus
==============================

The following menus are available on the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows:


 @{" Project " Link "CI-men-P"}              Project menu

 @{" Edit " Link "CI-men-E"}                 Edit menu

 @{" Settings " Link "men-Settings"}             Settings menu


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P"
@Next "CI-men-E"
@Toc "CI-men"

Control and Edit Windows Project menu
-------------------------------------

This menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows:


 @{" New Points     N " Link "CI-men-P-New"}                     Delete all points
 @{" Open Points... O " Link "CI-men-P-Open"}                     Read points from a file
 @{" Save           S " Link "CI-men-P-Save"}                     Save file
 @{" Save As...     A " Link "CI-men-P-Save_As"}                     Save named file
 @{" About... " Link "CI-men-P-About"}                             Show about requester
 @{" Exit Points " Link "CI-men-P-Exit_Points"}                          Open windows to edit points
 @{" Quit           Q " Link "CI-men-P-Quit"}                     Quit program


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-New" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-New"
@Next "CI-men-P-Open"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/New Points menu item
....................................................

This menu item deletes all existing points.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-Open" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-Open"
@Next "CI-men-P-Save"
@Prev "CI-men-P-New"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/Open Points menu item
.....................................................

This menu item allows the loading of a previously created
@{"Parameter file" Link "File_Format"}.

Only the points are loaded from the file. Other parameters are retained.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-Save" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-Save"
@Next "CI-men-P-Save_As"
@Prev "CI-men-P-Open"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/Save menu item
..............................................

This saves the current project using the current name. If the project
does not yet have a name then an ASL file requester is displayed.

See @{"File Format" Link "File_Format"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-Save_As" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-Save_As"
@Next "CI-men-P-About"
@Prev "CI-men-P-Save"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/Save As... menu item
....................................................

This saves the current project using a name chosen using an ASL file
requester.

See @{"File Format" Link "File_Format"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-About" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-About"
@Next "CI-men-P-Exit_Points"
@Prev "CI-men-P-Save_As"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/About... menu item
..................................................

This displays some program version information in the @{"About Requester" Link "Req-About"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-Exit_Points" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-Exit_Points"
@Next "CI-men-P-Quit"
@Prev "CI-men-P-About"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/Exit Points menu item
.....................................................

This is the same as closing the @{"Control Window" Link "Con-gad-Close"} or either of the
@{"Edit Windows" Link "E-gad-Close"}. It closes all of these windows.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-P-Quit" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-P-Quit"
@Prev "CI-men-P-Exit_Points"
@Toc "CI-men-P"

Control and Edit Window Project/Quit menu item
..............................................

This quits TSMorph.

If the current project has been changed but not saved then the
@{"Unsaved Project requester" Link "Req-Unsaved"} is displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E"
@Next "men-Settings"
@Prev "CI-men-P"
@Toc "CI-men"

Control and Edit Window Edit menu
---------------------------------

This menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows:


 @{" Add Grid... " Link "CI-men-E-Grid"}              Add a grid of points
 @{" Frame " Link "CI-men-E-Frame"}                    Change the Frame Number
 @{" Edit Mode " Link "CI-men-E-EMode"}                Set the edit mode.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Grid" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Grid"
@Next "CI-men-E-Frame"
@Toc "CI-men-E"

Control and Edit Window Edit/Add Grid... menu item
..................................................

This menu item displays the @{"Add Grid" Link "Req-Add_Grid"} requester to add a grid of points
to the images.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame"
@Next "CI-men-E-EMode"
@Prev "CI-men-E-Grid"
@Toc "CI-men-E"

Control and Edit Windows Frame sub menu
.......................................

This sub menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows:


 @{" First    < " Link "CI-men-E-Frame-First"}                        First Frame
 @{" Previous - " Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Previous"}                        Previous Frame
 @{" Goto...  . " Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Goto"}                        Goto Frame
 @{" Next     + " Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Next"}                        Next Frame
 @{" Last     > " Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Last"}                        Last Frame


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame-First" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame-First"
@Toc "CI-men-E-Frame"

Control and Edit Windows Frame/First item
*****************************************

This menu item goes to the first frame. This is the same as the @{"First" Link "Con-gad-First"}
gadget.

This menu item is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the
first frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame-Previous" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame-Previous"
@Toc "CI-men-E-Frame"

Control and Edit Windows Frame/Previous item
********************************************

This menu item goes to the previous frame. This is the same as the
@{"Previous" Link "Con-gad-Previous"} gadget.

This menu item is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the
first frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame-Goto" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame-Goto"
@Toc "CI-men-E-Frame"

Control and Edit Windows Frame/Goto item
****************************************

This menu item goes to a chosen frame. This is the same as the @{"Goto" Link "Con-gad-Goto"}
gadget. It displays the @{"Frame Number" Link "Req-FrameNumber"} Requester.

This menu item is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the
first frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame-Next" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame-Next"
@Toc "CI-men-E-Frame"

Control and Edit Windows Frame/Next item
****************************************

This menu item goes to the next frame. This is the same as the @{"Next" Link "Con-gad-Next"}
gadget.

This menu item is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the
last frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-Frame-Last" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-Frame-Last"
@Toc "CI-men-E-Frame"

Control and Edit Windows Frame/Last item
****************************************

This menu item goes to the last frame. This is the same as the @{"Last" Link "Con-gad-Last"}
gadget.

This menu item is disabled if the Morph/Warp is not animated, or the
last frame is already displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "CI-men-E-EMode" "TSMorph.guide/CI-men-E-EMode"
@Prev "CI-men-E-Frame"
@Toc "CI-men-E"

Control and Edit Window Edit/Mode sub menu
..........................................

This sub menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows:


 @{" Edit One  1 " Link "EMode-One"}               Move points in one window
 @{" Edit Two  2 " Link "EMode-Two"}               Move points in both windows
 @{" Edit Rel  3 " Link "EMode-Relative"}               Move points relatively in both windows
 @{" Add       4 " Link "EMode-Add"}               Add a new point
 @{" Delete    5 " Link "EMode-Delete"}               Delete an existing point
 @{" Link      6 " Link "EMode-Link"}               Link two points
 @{" Unlink    7 " Link "EMode-Unlink"}               Unlink two points
 @{" None      8 " Link "EMode-Move"}               Scroll the window


@EndNode

@Node "men-Settings" "TSMorph.guide/men-Settings"
@Prev "CI-men-E"
@Toc "CI-men"

Settings menu
-------------

This menu contains the following items with their associated Amiga
short-cuts in the @{"Control" Link "Con"}, @{"Info" Link "Info"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows. Settings can be set
using @{"Parameters" Link "Par"}. All menu items which display requesters will not be
available if reqtools.library is not available. Items requiring
opal.library will not be available if opal.library is not available.


 @{" Create Icons? " Link "P-CREATEICONS"}                      Create Icons on projects?
 @{" Change Palette?  P " Link "P-CHANGEPALETTE"}                 Use Image palette?
 @{" Zoom?            Z " Link "P-ZOOM"}                 Zoom Image?
 @{" Open Mode " Link "P-OPENMODE"}                          How to open images
 @{" Public Screen... " Link "P-PUBSCREEN"}                   Screen for TSMorph

 @{" Create Prefs Icons? " Link "P-CREATEICONSP"}                Create Icons on settings
 @{" Keep Settings? " Link "P-KEEPSETTINGS"}                     Keep settings on Quit
 @{" Load Settings... " Link "men-S-LoadS"}                   Display file requester to load settings
 @{" Save Settings " Link "men-S-SaveS"}                      Save settings in ENVARC:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs
 @{" Save Settings As... " Link "men-S-SaveSAs"}                Display file requester to save settings

 @{" Create Render Icons? " Link "P-CREATEICONSR"}               Create Icons on images?
 @{" DX... " Link "P-DX"}                              Horizontal skip
 @{" DY... " Link "P-DY"}                              Vertical skip
 @{" Load Script... " Link "P-LOADSCRIPT"}                     ARexx load script
 @{" Pre Script... " Link "P-PRESCRIPT"}                      ARexx pre frame script
 @{" Post Script... " Link "P-POSTSCRIPT"}                     ARexx post frame script
 @{" Depth " Link "P-DEPTH"}                              Morphing algorithm depth
 @{" Mode " Link "P-MODE"}                               Morphing algorithm mode
 @{" Save Format " Link "P-SAVEFORMAT"}                        Image save format
 @{" JPEG Quality " Link "P-QUALITY"}                       Quailty of JPEG images
 @{" Render Screen... " Link "P-PUBSCREENR"}                   Public screen for TSMorph-render

 @{" Reset To Defaults " Link "men-S-ResetD"}                  Reset to default settings
 @{" Last Saved " Link "men-S-LastS"}                         Restore from ENVARC:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs
 @{" Restore " Link "men-S-Restore"}                            Restore from ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-LoadS" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-LoadS"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Load Settings...
.............................

This displays an ASL requester to load @{"settings" Link "Par"} into the currently
running program.

The default name is TSMorph.prefs.


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-SaveS" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-SaveS"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Save Settings
..........................

This saves the current @{"settings" Link "Par"} in 'ENVARC:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs' and
'ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs'.

If @{"CREATEICONSP" Link "P-CREATEICONSP"} is set then an Icon is saved as well

Unless @{"KEEPSETTINGS" Link "P-KEEPSETTINGS"} is set to NO current settings are saved in
'ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs' whenever TSMorph is quit.


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-SaveSAs" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-SaveSAs"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Save Settings As...
................................

This displays an ASL requester to save the current @{"settings" Link "Par"}.

If @{"CREATEICONSP" Link "P-CREATEICONSP"} is set then an Icon is saved as well

The default name is TSMorph.prefs.


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-ResetD" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-ResetD"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Reset To Defaults
..............................

This resets @{"settings" Link "Par"} to there default values.

If some @{"Image windows" Link "Edit"} are open and @{"CHANGEPALETTE" Link "P-CHANGEPALETTE"} is set to OFF then it
will stay OFF. The same applies to @{"ZOOM" Link "P-ZOOM"}.


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-LastS" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-LastS"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Last Saved
.......................

This reset @{"settings" Link "Par"} to the values last saved in
ENVARC:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs (overridden by any TOOLTYPES).

If some @{"Image windows" Link "Edit"} are open and @{"CHANGEPALETTE" Link "P-CHANGEPALETTE"} is set to OFF then it
will stay OFF. The same applies to @{"ZOOM" Link "P-ZOOM"}.


@EndNode

@Node "men-S-Restore" "TSMorph.guide/men-S-Restore"
@Toc "men-Settings"

Setting menu/Restore
....................

This resets @{"settings" Link "Par"} to the values last saved in
ENV:TSMorph/TSMorph.prefs (overridden by any TOOLTYPES). Settings are
saved in this file whenever TSMorph is quit if @{"KEEPSETTINGS" Link "P-KEEPSETTINGS"} is set to
YES.

If some @{"Image windows" Link "Edit"} are open and @{"CHANGEPALETTE" Link "P-CHANGEPALETTE"} is set to OFF then it
will stay OFF. The same applies to @{"ZOOM" Link "P-ZOOM"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Con-Key" "TSMorph.guide/Con-Key"
@Toc "Con"

Keyboard controls in the Control Window
=======================================

'Help' displays context sensitive help using amigaguide if available.


@EndNode

@Node "Edit" "TSMorph.guide/Edit"
@Next "EModes"
@Prev "Con"
@Toc "Main"

The Edit Windows
****************

The Edit windows display Workbench displayable versions of the images
to be morphed along with the control points. The window title displays
the file name, the screen title displays the full file name. The mouse
pointer shows the current editing mode. The windows are sizeable and
have scrollbars. The menus displayed are the same as the @{"Control Window" Link "Con"}.

The first click in these windows is ignored.


 @{" Gadgets " Link "E-gad"}       Gadgets on the Edit Windows
 @{" Menus " Link "CI-men"}         Menus on the Edit Windows
 @{" Keyboard " Link "E-key"}      Keyboard controls on the Edit Windows
 @{" Modes " Link "EModes"}         Point editing modes.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad"
@Toc "Edit"

Gadgets on the Edit Windows
===========================

The Edit Windows appears with gadgets:

     -------------------
     |.|filename |  |  |
     ------------------|
     |              |  |
     |              ||||
     |              ||||
     |              ||||
     |              |  |
     |              |/\|
     |              |\/|
     |-----------------|
     | ------- <- ->|//|
     |------------------


 @{" Horizontal scroll gadget " Link "E-gad-Horiz"}            Scrolls image horizontally
 @{" Vertical scroll gadget " Link "E-gad-Vert"}              Scrolls image vertically
 @{" Up gadget " Link "E-gad-Up"}                           Scroll image up
 @{" Down gadget " Link "E-gad-Down"}                         Scroll image down
 @{" Left gadget " Link "E-gad-Left"}                         Scroll image left
 @{" Right gadget " Link "E-gad-Right"}                        Scroll image right

 @{" Close gadget " Link "E-gad-Close"}                        Close Edit and Control Windows
 @{" Zoom gadget " Link "E-gad-Zoom"}                         Zoom window
 @{" Depth gadget " Link "E-gad-Depth"}                        Depth gadget
 @{" Sizing gadget " Link "E-gad-Size"}                       Sizing gadget


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Horiz" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Horiz"
@Next "E-gad-Vert"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Horizontal gadget
------------------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image horizontally.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Vert" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Vert"
@Next "E-gad-Up"
@Prev "E-gad-Horiz"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Vertical gadget
----------------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image vertically.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Up" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Up"
@Next "E-gad-Down"
@Prev "E-gad-Vert"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Up gadget
----------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image up.

Holding down shift will cause the window to scroll one pixel at a time.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Down" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Down"
@Next "E-gad-Left"
@Prev "E-gad-Up"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Down gadget
------------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image down.

Holding down shift will cause the window to scroll one pixel at a time.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Left" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Left"
@Next "E-gad-Right"
@Prev "E-gad-Down"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Left gadget
------------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image left.

Holding down shift will cause the window to scroll one pixel at a time.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Right" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Right"
@Next "E-gad-Close"
@Prev "E-gad-Left"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Right gadget
-------------------------

This gadget can be used to scroll the image right.

Holding down shift will cause the window to scroll one pixel at a time.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Close" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Close"
@Next "E-gad-Zoom"
@Prev "E-gad-Right"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Close gadget
-------------------------

This closes the @{"Control Window" Link "Con"}, and the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Zoom" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Zoom"
@Next "E-gad-Depth"
@Prev "E-gad-Close"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Zoom gadget
------------------------

This is a standard Zoom gadget. It swaps the size between maximum and
minimum

Maximum is the smaller of the size of the image or the size of the
screen.

Minimum is the minimum required for all gadgets to still be visible.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Depth" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Depth"
@Next "E-gad-Size"
@Prev "E-gad-Zoom"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Depth gadget
-------------------------

This is a standard depth gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "E-gad-Size" "TSMorph.guide/E-gad-Size"
@Prev "E-gad-Depth"
@Toc "E-gad"

Edit Windows Sizing gadget
--------------------------

This a standard sizing gadget. See @{"Zoom" Link "E-gad-Zoom"} gadget for the sizing limits


@EndNode

@Node "E-Key" "TSMorph.guide/E-Key"
@Toc "Edit"

Keyboard controls in the Edit Windows
=====================================

'Help' displays context sensitive help using amigaguide if available.


@EndNode

@Node "EModes" "TSMorph.guide/EModes"
@Next "Req"
@Prev "Edit"
@Toc "Main"

Point editing modes
*******************

The following edit modes are available to edit points:


 @{" One " Link "EMode-One"}                    Move points in one window
 @{" Two " Link "EMode-Two"}                    Move points in both windows
 @{" Relative " Link "EMode-Relative"}               Move points relatively in both windows
 @{" Add " Link "EMode-Add"}                    Add a new point
 @{" Delete " Link "EMode-Delete"}                 Delete an existing point
 @{" Link " Link "EMode-Link"}                   Link two points
 @{" Unlink " Link "EMode-Unlink"}                 Unlink two points
 @{" Move " Link "EMode-Move"}                   Scroll the window

Note: The menu button can always be used to abort the current operation
before releasing the select button.

Modes can be set using gadgets in the @{"Control Window" Link "Con-gad"} or by using @{"menus" Link "CI-men-E-EMode"}
on the @{"Control" Link "Con"} and @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} Windows.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-One" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-One"
@Next "EMode-Two"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode One
=============

This mode is used to move a point in one of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "One".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "ONE".

Points can be clicked and moved in either of the windows with the mouse
- the point will only move in the selected window.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Two" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Two"
@Next "EMode-Relative"
@Prev "EMode-One"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Two
=============

This mode is used to move a point in both of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "Two".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "TWO".

Points can be clicked and moved in both of the windows with the mouse -
the point will move in both windows to the same absolute position.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Relative" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Relative"
@Next "EMode-Add"
@Prev "EMode-Two"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Relative
==================

This mode is used to move a point in both of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "Rel".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "REL".

Points can be clicked and moved in both of the windows with the mouse -
the point will move in both windows to the same relative position.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Add" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Add"
@Next "EMode-Delete"
@Prev "EMode-Relative"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Add
=============

This mode is used to add a point in both of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "Add".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "ADD".

Points can be added in either of the windows by clicking the mouse - the
point will added to both windows to the same absolute position.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Delete" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Delete"
@Next "EMode-Link"
@Prev "EMode-Add"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Delete
================

This mode is used to delete a point in both of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "Del".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "DEL".

Points can be deleted in either of the windows by clicking the mouse -
the point will deleted from both windows. Any @{"links" Link "EMode-link"} will also be
removed.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Link" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Link"
@Next "EMode-Unlink"
@Prev "EMode-Delete"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Link
==============

This mode is used to link two points in both of the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is initially set to "L1".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "L1".

A point can then be selected in either of the windows by clicking the
mouse.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is then set to "L2".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "L2".

Another point can then be selected in either of the windows by clicking
the mouse. The points will be joined by a line.

Note: this line is to enable points to be identified more easily. It is
not used by the rendering process.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Unlink" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Unlink"
@Next "EMode-Move"
@Prev "EMode-Link"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Unlink
================

This mode is used to unlink two linked points in both of the
@{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"}.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is initially set to "U1".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "U1".

A point can then be selected in either of the windows by clicking the
mouse.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is then set to "U2".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "U2".

Another point can then be selected in either of the windows by clicking
the mouse. If the points are currently joined then the line will be
removed.


@EndNode

@Node "EMode-Move" "TSMorph.guide/EMode-Move"
@Prev "EMode-Unlink"
@Toc "EModes"

Edit Mode Move
==============

In this mode no points are edited.

The @{"Control Windows" Link "Con"} title is set to "Mov".

The Mouse Pointer is set to "Mov".

Clicking in the window and moving the mouse will scroll the window.

This is the initial mode when the @{"Edit Windows" Link "Edit"} are opened.


@EndNode

@Node "Req" "TSMorph.guide/Req"
@Next "Interface"
@Prev "EModes"
@Toc "Main"

Requesters which appear
***********************

The following requesters are produced:


 @{" Unsaved Project " Link "Req-Unsaved"}              Quitting having not saved
 @{" About requester " Link "Req-About"}              Version Information
 @{" Error requester " Link "Req-Error"}              Error messages
 @{" Add Grid " Link "Req-Add_Grid"}                     Add a grid of points
 @{" Frame Number? " Link "Req-FrameNumber"}                Choose a Frame Number

 @{" Progress " Link "Req-Progress"}                     Progress
 @{" Really quit? " Link "Req-Really_quit"}                 Really quit?


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Unsaved" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Unsaved"
@Next "Req-About"
@Toc "Req"

Unsaved project requester
=========================

This requester is displayed when attempting to quit with having saved a
project.

It displays 3 or 4 options (depending on if amigaguide is available):

     Save:    Save the project and quit
     Help:    Display help (only shown if available)
     Abandon: Quit without saving the project
     Cancel:  Do not save and do not quit

If reqtools.library(38) is available then this will be used and
keyboard short-cuts (the first character of the option) will be
available and underlined.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-About" "TSMorph.guide/Req-About"
@Next "Req-Error"
@Prev "Req-Unsaved"
@Toc "Req"

About requester
===============

This requester is displayed when About... is chosen on a menu on the
@{"Info Window" Link "I-men-P-About"} or @{"Control or Edit Windows" Link "CI-men-P-About"}. It displays version information.

If reqtools.library(38) is available then this will be used and
keyboard short-cuts (the first character of the option) will be
available and underlined.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Error" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Error"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid"
@Prev "Req-About"
@Toc "Req"

Error requesters
================

This requester is displayed if an error occurs. It displays an error
message and gives one (or two) options.

If amigaguide is available then the first option will be "Help" - this
will display detailed information on the error message.

The last option is "Quit" for fatal errors, and "OK" for non fatal
errors.

See @{"Errors" Link "Errors"} for details on error messages.

If reqtools.library(38) is available then this will be used and
keyboard short-cuts (the first character of the option) will be
available and underlined.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid"
@Next "Req-FrameNumber"
@Prev "Req-Error"
@Toc "Req"

Add Grid requester
==================

The Add Grid requester appears as below when the @{"Add Grid..." Link "CI-men-E-Grid"} menu item
is chosen

     --------------
     |.|Add Grid| |
     -------------|
     | X Cells .. |
     | Y Cells .. |
     |            |
     | OK  Cancel |
     --------------

The following gadgets are displayed in the requester with their
associated keyboard equivalents:


 @{" X Cells   X " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-X_Cells"}                         Set number of X cells
 @{" Y Cells   Y " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells"}                         Set number of Y Cells
 @{" OK        O " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-OK"}                         Add points
 @{" Cancel    C " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel"}                         Cancel requester
 @{" Close       " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Close"}                         Close gadget
 @{" Depth       " Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Depth"}                         Depth gadget


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-X_Cells" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-X_Cells"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid X Cells gadget
-----------------------

This gadget is used to input the number of horizontal cells of points
to add. The minimum number is 1. The default value displayed is 5.

This gadget can be activated by using the X key.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid-gad-OK"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid-gad-X_Cells"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid Y Cells gadget
-----------------------

This gadget is used to input the number of vertical cells of points to
add. The minimum number is 1. The default value displayed is 5.

This gadget can be activated by using the Y key.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-OK" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-OK"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid OK gadget
------------------

Selecting this gadget adds points of cells to the images. The number of
horizontal cells can be set in the @{"X Cells" Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-X_Cells"} gadget and the number of
vertical cells in the @{"Y Cells" Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Y_Cells"} gadget.

The O key is the same as using this gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Close"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid-gad-OK"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid Cancel gadget
----------------------

This gadget cancels the Add Grid requester without adding any points.

The C key is the same as using this gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Close" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-Close"
@Next "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Depth"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid Close gadget
---------------------

This is the same as the @{"Cancel" Link "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Cancel"} gadget and cancels the requester.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Depth" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Add_Grid-gad-Depth"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid-gad-Close"
@Toc "Req-Add_Grid"

Add Grid Depth gadget
---------------------

This is a standard depth gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-FrameNumber" "TSMorph.guide/Req-FrameNumber"
@Next "Req-Progress"
@Prev "Req-Add_Grid"
@Toc "Req"

Choose a Frame Number requester
===============================

This requester is displayed when the @{"Edit Points" Link "I-gad-Edit_Points"} gadget is selected
(and there is more than one frame) on an animated Morph/Warp, or the
@{"Goto" Link "Con-gad-Goto"} gadget or @{"Goto" Link "CI-men-E-Frame-Goto"} menu item is selected.

It displays the first and last frame number and allows input of the
required frame number.

It displays 'Ok', 'Help' (if amigaguide is available) and 'Cancel'
gadgets. The keyboard shortcuts (O,H and C) are underlined.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Progress" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Progress"
@Next "Req-Really_quit"
@Prev "Req-FrameNumber"
@Toc "Req"

Progress requester
==================

This requester is displayed by TSMorph-render. It shows an information
line, and the current frame and line being calculated.

It also displays a "stop" button and a zoom and depth gadget.

The "stop" gadget is checked every line. Clicking it displays the
@{"Really quit?" Link "Req-Really_quit"} requester allowing the program to be stopped.

The 'Help' key displays help.


@EndNode

@Node "Req-Really_quit" "TSMorph.guide/Req-Really_quit"
@Prev "Req-Progress"
@Toc "Req"

Really quit? requester
======================

This requester is displayed when the "stop" gadget is clicked on the
@{"Progress" Link "Req-Progress"} requester. It displays two (or three) options "Quit" ("Help")
and "Continue". "Quit" quits the program, "Continue" restarts the
calculation, "Help" is displayed if amigaguide is available and
displays help.

If reqtools.library(38) is available then this will be used and
keyboard short-cuts (the first character of the option) will be
available and underlined.


@EndNode

@Node "Interface" "TSMorph.guide/Interface"
@Next "File_Format"
@Prev "Req"
@Toc "Main"

Changing the Interface
**********************

All the gadgets in the @{"Control" Link "Con-gad"} window, and the mouse pointers can be
edited.

The brushes are stored in the directory "Brush/". All may be edited and
using e.g. DPaint.

The following brushes are size 38x34:

     add
     del
     link
     none
     one
     rel
     two
     unlink

The following are 15x15:

     1st
     Last
     Next
     Prev

The following is 16x15:

     Goto

The mouse pointers are stored in the directory "Cursor/". All may be
edited using the Workbench Pointer editor,

The following Pointers can be edited:

     Xadd
     Xdel
     Xl1
     Xl2
     Xmov
     Xone
     Xrel
     Xtwo
     Xu1
     Xu2


@EndNode

@Node "File_Format" "TSMorph.guide/File_Format"
@Next "AR"
@Prev "Interface"
@Toc "Main"

Internal file formats
*********************

The file format is subject to change at any time.

The current format for the main file is:

     TSMorph 1.2
     file_name_one
     file_name_two
     24_bit_file_name_1
     24_bit_file_name_2
     anim_file_name
     w=a,h=b,Frames=c,Single=d,Start=e
     x=n,y=m,x1=o,y1=p
     .
     .
     .
     p1=i,p2=j
     .
     .
     .

where "TSMorph 1.2" is a header record (not present in the previous
version of TSMorph, old formats can still be loaded producing a
@{"warning message" Link "Err-OldFormat"}), a is the width, b the height, c the number of frames,
d is 1 for single mode, 0 for dual, n,m are coordinates on the first
image, o,p on the second image, and i and j are the number of the
points to join (starting from 0).

For animated Warps and Morphs the main file contains no points. Each
frame has a set of points held in a file named with .nnn after the main
file name, where nnn is the frame number. This file has a header of
'TSMorph 2.0' and then has the Points details.


@EndNode

@Node "AR" "TSMorph.guide/AR"
@Next "Algorithms"
@Prev "File_Format"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx interface to TSMorph-render
*********************************

ARexx scripts are run before and after each image is rendered, and
before each 24 bit image is loaded. The script names can be supplied as
parameters (@{"LOADSCRIPT" Link "P-LOADSCRIPT"}, @{"PRESCRIPT" Link "P-PRESCRIPT"} and @{"POSTSCRIPT" Link "P-POSTSCRIPT"}) to TSMorph-render.
The suffix to each ARexx script should be .TSM.


 @{" Loadscript " Link "AR-Loadscript"}              Run before loading 24 bit image
 @{" Prescript " Link "AR-Prescript"}               Run before rendering
 @{" Postscript " Link "AR-Postscript"}              Run after rendering


@EndNode

@Node "AR-Loadscript" "TSMorph.guide/AR-Loadscript"
@Next "AR-Prescript"
@Toc "AR"

ARexx sxript run before loading 24 bit image
============================================

This script is run before each 24 bit ILBM image is loaded.

It is passed the following parameters:

     Frame       : The current frame number, starting at @{"Start" Link "I-gad-Start"}.
     TotalFrames : The total number of frames being rendered.
     Single      : Set to 1 if a Warp, 0 for a Morph, 2 for Anim Morph, 3 for Anim Warp.
     Image       : Set to 0 for 1st image, 1 for second.
     FileName    : Name of file just rendered.

This script can be used to change the format of the input file (by
running it through a conversion program).

One example is included:

     @{"Loadscript.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/Loadscript.TSM/Main} - Do nothing example


@EndNode

@Node "AR-Prescript" "TSMorph.guide/AR-Prescript"
@Next "AR-Postscript"
@Prev "AR-Loadscript"
@Toc "AR"

ARexx script run before rendering
=================================

This script is run before each image is rendered.

It is passed one parameter - Base - the address of a structure which
contains the following:

     Frame       = 0  : The current frame number, starting at 1 - read only.
     TotalFrames = 1  : The total number of frames being rendered - read only.
     Single      = 2  : Set to 1 if a Warp, 0 = Morph, 2 = Anim Morph, 3 = Anim Warp - read only.
     Movement    = 3  : 0 to 1024 - the proportion of movement from first to second image.
     Red1        = 4  : 0 to 1024 - the proportion of Image 1 Red to use.
     Green1      = 5  : As Red1 for Green.
     Blue1       = 6  : As Red1 for Blue.
     Red2        = 7  : 0 to 1024 - the proportion of Image 2 Red to use.
     Green2      = 8  : As Red2 for Green.
     Blue2       = 9  : As Red2 for Blue.
     Produce     = 10 : Set to 0 to not render this frame, 1 otherwise.
     RPlus       = 11 : 0 to 255 to add to Red in rendered image.
     GPlus       = 12 : As RPlus for Green.
     BPlus       = 13 : As RPlus for Blue.
     RMinus      = 14 : 0 to 255 to subtract from Red in rendered image.
     GMinus      = 15 : As RMinus for Green.
     BMinus      = 16 : As RMinus for Blue.
     DX          = 17 : 0 to ? - X amount to skip - See @{"parameters" Link "Par-TSMorph-render"}.
     DY          = 18 : 0 to ? - Y amount to skip - See @{"parameters" Link "Par-TSMorph-render"}.
     Start       = 19 : Starting frame number.

The values of these parameters may be set and read using the GetValue
and StoreValue functions:

     /* To read the value of e.g Movement use:
        integer_variable = GetValue(Base,Movement)
     */
     
     /* To set the value of e.g. Produce to 0 use:
        call StoreValue(Base,Produce,0)
     */
     
     GetValue:Procedure
        Parse arg XBase, XAdd
        return C2D(IMPORT(D2C(STRIP(XBase) + (STRIP(Xadd) * 4)),4))
     
     StoreValue:Procedure
        Parse arg XBase, XAdd, XVal
        call EXPORT(D2C(STRIP(XBase) + (STRIP(Xadd) * 4)),RIGHT(D2C(XVal),4,D2C(0)),4)
        return

The default values passed to the script for modification are:

     Movement            : (1024 * Frame)/(TotalFrames + 1) Morphs
                           (1024 * Frame)/TotalFrames       Warps
     
     Red1,Green1,Blue1   : Movement                         Morphs
                           1024                             Warps
     
     Red2,Green2,Blue2   : (1024 - Movement)                Morphs
                           0                 Irrelevant for Warps
     
     Produce             : 1
     RPlus,GPlus,BPlus   : 0
     PMinus,GMinus,BMinus: 0
     DX,DY               : Initially set by @{"DX" Link "P-DX"} and @{"DY" Link "P-DY"} parameters

Changing these values allows acceleration of movement, colour fades
etc. and the generation of only some images (to check a long animation).

Example scripts include are:

     @{"FadeToBlack.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/FadeToBlack.TSM/Main"} - Warp fade to black
     @{"FadeToWhite.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/FadeToWhite.TSM/Main"} - Warp fade to white
     @{"PixelMorph.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/PixelMorph.TSM/Main"}  - Morph by pixelating
     @{"PixelWarp.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/PixelWarp.TSM/Main"}   - Warp pixelating
     @{"Prescript.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/Prescript.TSM/Main"}   - Do nothing example


@EndNode

@Node "AR-Postscript" "TSMorph.guide/AR-Postscript"
@Prev "AR-Prescript"
@Toc "AR"

ARexx script run after rendering
================================

This script is run after each image is rendered.

It is passed the following parameters:

     Frame       : The current frame number, starting at @{"Start" Link "I-gad-Start"}.
     TotalFrames : The total number of frames being rendered.
     Single      : Set to 1 if a Warp, 0 for a Morph.
     FileName    : Name of file just rendered.

This script can be used to change the format of the output file (by
running it through a conversion program) or build an animation.

Two examples are included:

     @{"Postscript.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/Postscript.TSM/Main} - Do nothing example
     @{"ToHam.TSM" ALINK "Rexx/ToHam.TSM/Main}      - Convert using PPM and Wasp


@EndNode

@Node "Algorithms" "TSMorph.guide/Algorithms"
@Next "File_Names"
@Prev "AR"
@Toc "Main"

Morphing algorithms
*******************

The morphing algorithm is defined using the parameters @{"MODE" Link "P-MODE"} and @{"DEPTH" Link "P-DEPTH"}
to TSMorph-render.

The basic algorithm is to find 3 points which make a triangle around
the point and morph this triangle between the start and end images.

The DEPTH parameter controls how many points will be checked to form a
triangle. 0 means just the closest 3 points are examined, 1 the closest
4, 2 the closest 5 etc.

The MODE parameter controls both which triangle is chosen and what to
do if no surrounding triangle is found.

If MODE=0 or MODE=2 then if no triangle surrounding the point is found
examining the closest points then the 3 closest points are used to
decide how to morph. If MODE=1 or MODE=3 then the point is assumed to
be stationery.

If MODE=2 or MODE=3 then all the closest points (the exact number
defined by DEPTH) are examined to determine the smallest triangle. If
MODE=0 or MODE=1 then the first surrounding triangle found is used.

Therefore MODEs 0 and 1 should be faster than modes 2 or 3. The DEPTH
parameter can also have a major effect on the rendering speed.


@EndNode

@Node "File_Names" "TSMorph.guide/File_Names"
@Next "Errors"
@Prev "Algorithms"
@Toc "Main"

File naming
***********

File names can include the frame number.

The format of the frame number in the file name is specified using the
following formats:

     %ld     : Number left justified e.g. '1','2',..,'10',..,'123',..
     %3ld    : Number right justified e.g. '  1','  2',..,' 10',..,'123',..
     %03ld   : Number right justified e.g. '001','002',..,'010',..,'123',..

Where the number can be changed e.g.

     pic.%04ld   for Imagine 2.0 produced files
     pic%03ld    for Vista produced files
     name%ld     for files to run through mpeg


@EndNode

@Node "Errors" "TSMorph.guide/Errors"
@Next "Bugs"
@Prev "File_Names"
@Toc "Main"

